<DOC><DOCNO> AP890218-0057 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-89 1803EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-18 0405</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0415</SECOND><HEAD>Ice And Heavy Snow Over virginia And Carolinas, Washington</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy snow fell Saturday over the central Atlantic Coast and theNorthwest, while light snow fell over the northern Plains.   A low-pressure system off the coast of North Carolina circulatedmoisture from the Atlantic back over Virginia and the Carolinas,producing ice and heavy snow.   Winter storm warnings were posted for upstate South Carolina,western and northern North Carolina, and south-central and easternVirginia.   By midday, Norfolk, Va., had 11.2 inches of snow, the secondhighest total on record there for February. Up to 14 inches of snowhad fallen at Williamsburg, Va., and in northern North Carolina'sWarren and Stokes counties.   Sleet and freezing rain coated other parts of Virginia and theCarolinas, and ice accumulating on branches and power lines causedscattered power outages in the Carolinas.   In the Northwest, steady snow fell Saturday on the easterntwo-thirds of Washington state as the most severe snowstorm to hitthe state this winter slowed traffic to a crawl, especially inmountain passes. Spokane, Wash., had 13 inches of new snow.   A winter storm warning was posted throughout the night for thecentral mountains and northern panhandle of Idaho, where up to 8inches of snow was possible.   Light snow fell was over parts of Minnesota, South Dakota,Nebraska, Iowa, Illinois and Wisconsin.   Rain fell over the northern and central Pacific Coast region, andover the central Gulf Coast states.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6degrees below zero at Glasgow and Havre, Mont., to 84 at Fort Myers,Fla. Saturday morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 33 degreesbelow zero at Hibbing, Minn.   For Sunday, snow was forecast from the western Rockies to themiddle Mississippi Valley. Scattered snow showers were forecast overthe Northeast. Rain was forecast over the northern Pacific Coast,with scattered showers across the central Pacific Coast. Widelyscattered showers were forecast over south-central Texas and theSoutheast.   Highs remaining below freezing were predicted from easternWashington state through Nebraska and the Dakotas to New England,with highs only in the teens from northern Montana to northernMinnesota, and over northern Maine; above 50 from the coast ofCalifornia through the southern Plains to the southern AtlanticCoast; in the 70s in the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and lower80s across the Florida Peninsula.</TEXT></DOC>